\f1\b \cf0 How to build a button...
\f0\b0 \
In this sample, each image was broken into three parts instead of 9 pieces. The left and right parts were given fixed width values. Consider the whiteButton.png, a 29x46 PNG image that was used to build the "iPhone" button in this sample. The height of its top and bottom parts was set to 0. Thus, making the whiteButton.png image, a three-piece image. Its left and right sides are 14 pixels wide. Thus leaving 1 pixel for the body.\
The result is a button whose body can horizontally scale while its left and right corners are stationary. The "blue," "white," "black," "blackLeft," and "blackRight" classes in the "iPhoneButtons.css" file are respectively used to build the "iPhone," "iPod classic," "iPod nano," "iPod shuffle," and "iPod touch" buttons. \
\

\f1\b How to style a button...
\f0\b0 \
The "button" class in the "iPhoneButton.css" illustrates how to style all the buttons. Set the display attribute to block so each button's height and width can be easily adjusted. The buttons will expand to the width of their parent cell unless their width is specified. The "line-height" attribute is used to vertically align text on each button.  \
