\f1\b About the -webkit-border-image ...
\f0\b0 \
The -webkit-border-image is a WebKit extension that builds borders using images in Safari 3. It is based on the proposed W3C CSS3 border-image property. It divides an image into four corners, four edges and a middle part, which can expands horizontally. \
Its syntax is:\
	-webkit-border-image: url(image-path) first second third fourth shape shape\
\
The url(image-path) specifies the image to be used, first is the height of the top edge and of the two top corners, second is the width of the right edge and the two right corners, third is the height of the bottom edge and the two bottom corners and fourth is the width of the left edge and the two left corners.\
shape, which is either "round" or "stretch", specifies how the image fits into the border. Both shape values are optional and may be omitted in a -webkit-border-image declaration. \
The first, second, third, and fourth should be given in either numbers or percentage. The numbers are either pixels in an image (if the image is a raster image) or CSS px units (if not). The percentages values are relative to the size of an image.	 \
Further documentation about the CSS3 border-image can be found at {\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "http://www.w3.org/TR/css3-border/#the-border-image"}}{\fldrslt http://www.w3.org/TR/css3-border/#the-border-image}} .\
\
Usage examples are given below:\
    -webkit-border-image: url(example.png) 2 4 5 6 stretch \
    -webkit-border-image: url(example.png) 20% 25% 30% 25% round round\
\
\

\f1\b IMPORTANT...
\f0\b0 \
The following expression is invalid \
			 -webkit-border-image: url(example.png) 2px 4px 5px 6px \
\
You cannot add "px" after the 2, 4, 5 and 6 numbers in this expression.  The 2, 4, 5 and 6 values represent pixels in the example.png  image (if example.png is a raster image) or CSS px units (if not). Thus, the above expression should be written as follows:\
                             -webkit-border-image: url(example.png) 2 4 5 6\
\
